{compressed_context}

LAST AGENT OUTPUT:
{last_agent_output}

After each agent call, respond with:
{
  'reasoning': 'one-sentence explanation of why you called this agent and what you expected',
  'node_id': 'the node just executed',
  'next_action': 'CONTINUE | RETRY | ESCALATE | OPEN_HUMAN_GATE | COMPLETE',
  'next_node_id': 'which node to execute next (null if COMPLETE or ESCALATE)'
}

For the final COMPLETE action, also include:
{
  'final_summary': 'concise summary of what was accomplished',
  'artefacts': [list of produced artefacts with their locations],
  'warnings': [list of any non-fatal issues encountered]
}

agentAsToolRegistration.toolSchema:
Each agent registered with the orchestrator is wrapped as an Anthropic-compatible tool with the following schema structure:

{
  'name': '<snake_case_agent_id>',                        // e.g. 'developer_agent', 'security_scan_agent'
  'description': '<80-120 word rich description>',       // The single most important field for tool selection accuracy
  'input_schema': {
    'type': 'object',
    'properties': {
      'task_description': {'type': 'string', 'description': 'Human-readable description of what to do'},
      'context': {'type': 'object', 'description': 'Relevant context from previous steps (artefact IDs, summaries)'},
      'inputs': {'type': 'object', 'description': 'Typed inputs specific to this agent; see agent spec'},
      'priority': {'type': 'string', 'enum': ['low','normal','high'], 'default': 'normal'},
      'timeout_override_seconds': {'type': 'integer', 'description': 'Override default timeout if known to be slow task'}
    },
    'required': ['task_description', 'inputs']
  },
  'output_schema': {
    'type': 'object',
    'properties': {
      'status': {'type': 'string', 'enum': ['success', 'partial', 'failed']},
      'result': {'type': 'object', 'description': 'Agent-specific structured output'},
      'artefacts': {'type': 'array', 'items': {'type': 'object', 'properties': {'id': {'type': 'string'}, 'type': {'type': 'string'}, 'location': {'type': 'string'}}}},
      'warnings': {'type': 'array', 'items': {'type': 'string'}},
      'error': {'type': 'string', 'description': 'Present only when status=failed'}
    }
  }
}

DESCRIPTION TEMPLATE for agent descriptions (critical for orchestrator tool selection):
'Use this agent when: [primary use case in one sentence]. This agent specialises in: [3-5 bullet capability list]. It accepts: [key input types]. It produces: [key output types]. Do NOT use this agent for: [2-3 anti-examples to prevent misrouting]. Typical latency: [low/medium/high]. Requires prior output from: [prerequisite agents if any, or none].'

database.partitioningStrategy:
"execution_logs grows at O(events_per_step * steps_per_run * runs_per_day). At moderate load (100 runs/day, 20 steps/run, 50 events/step) this is 100,000 rows/day = 3M rows/month. Partition by RANGE on created_at using monthly partitions.

Postgres declarative partitioning:
  CREATE TABLE execution_logs (id UUID NOT NULL, run_id UUID NOT NULL, step_execution_id UUID, event_type VARCHAR(100) NOT NULL, level VARCHAR(10) NOT NULL DEFAULT 'info', payload JSONB NOT NULL DEFAULT '{}', created_at TIMESTAMPTZ NOT NULL DEFAULT NOW()) PARTITION BY RANGE (created_at);

  CREATE TABLE execution_logs_2026_01 PARTITION OF execution_logs FOR VALUES FROM ('2026-01-01') TO ('2026-02-01');
  CREATE TABLE execution_logs_2026_02 PARTITION OF execution_logs FOR VALUES FROM ('2026-02-01') TO ('2026-03-01');
  -- etc.

Primary key must include the partition key: PRIMARY KEY (id, created_at).

Indexes are created per partition:
  CREATE INDEX idx_el_2026_01_run_time ON execution_logs_2026_01 (run_id, created_at ASC);

Automate partition creation: Use a pg_cron job (or application startup check) to create next month's partition on the 25th of each month.

Retention policy: Drop partitions older than N months. 'DROP TABLE execution_logs_2024_06' is instant — no row-by-row DELETE required. This is the primary performance benefit of partitioning.

Alternative — TimescaleDB hypertable (if TimescaleDB is already in use for the host project): SELECT create_hypertable('execution_logs', 'created_at', chunk_time_interval => INTERVAL '1 month'); TimescaleDB manages partition creation automatically and adds columnar compression: SELECT add_compression_policy('execution_logs', INTERVAL '3 months').

SQLite alternative: No partitioning. Implement a nightly job that moves rows older than 30 days from execution_logs into an execution_logs_archive table. Use triggers or application logic to enforce this."
